{"title_page": "Sanford Bishop", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Sanford Bishop\n|image         = Sanford Bishop.jpg\n|state         = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|district      = {{ushr|GA|2|2nd}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 1993\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = Georgia\n|district1     = 15th\n|term_start1   = January 3, 1991\n|term_end1     = January 3, 1993\n|predecessor1  = Gary Parker \n|successor1    = [[Ed Harbison]]\n|state_house2  = Georgia\n|district2     = 94th\n|term_start2   = January 3, 1977\n|term_end2     = January 3, 1991\n|predecessor2  = C. Ed Berry\n|successor2    = Bill Lee\n|birth_name    = Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1947|2|4}}\n|birth_place   = [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = Vivian Creighton\n|children      = 1\n|education     = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Emory University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 1968\u20131971\n}}\n'''Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.''' (born February 4, 1947) is an American politician and chicken f***er serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|GA|2}}, serving since 1993. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. The district is located in the southwestern part of the state and includes [[Albany, Georgia|Albany]], [[Thomasville, Georgia|Thomasville]], and most of [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]] and [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nBishop was born in [[Mobile, Alabama]] to Minnie B. Slade and Sanford Dixon Bishop,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~battle/reps/bishopsd.htm |title=1. Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.: b. 4 Feb 1947 Mobile, Mobile Co., AL; U.S. Representative from GA (D)|website=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> who was the first president of [[Bishop State Community College]]. He was educated at [[Morehouse College]] and [[Emory University School of Law]], and served in the [[United States Army]].<ref name=\"navyleague\">{{cite web| title = Veterans in the US House of Representatives 109th Congress|publisher=Navy League|url=http://www.navyleague.org/legislative_affairs/HouseVets.pdf|format=PDF |accessdate=2007-10-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626235918/http://www.navyleague.org/legislative_affairs/HouseVets.pdf|archivedate=2007-06-26}}</ref> While at Morehouse, he was a classmate of [[Herman Cain]]. After receiving his honorable discharge, Bishop operated a law firm in [[Columbus, Georgia]].\n\nHe has received the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] from the [[Boy Scouts of America]] (BSA), given to [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scouts]] for distinguished career achievement.<ref name=\"honor\">{{Cite book|last=Townley|first=Alvin |url=http://www.thomasdunnebooks.com/TD_TitleDetail.aspx?ISBN=0312366531|title=Legacy of Honor: The Values and Influence of America's Eagle Scouts|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|pages=165\u201372|isbn=0-312-36653-1|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\"desalista\">{{cite web |url = http://www.scouting.org/filestore/pdf/02-529.pdf |title = Distinguished Eagle Scouts |publisher=Scouting.org|accessdate = 2010-11-04}}</ref> He is a member of BSA's [[Order of the Arrow]] (OA) and as a youth was on the OA ceremonies team.<ref name=\"honor\"/> He is a resident of [[Albany, Georgia]], where he is a member of the Mount Zion Baptist Church.  Bishop is a Life Member of [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity, initiated at Morehouse's Pi chapter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070530220133/http://bishop.house.gov/Bishop-photogallery.cfm?CD=21&ImgID=34&StartRow=4|title=Congressman Sanford Bishop, Jr.|date=2007-05-30|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>  Bishop is a [[Shriner]] and 33\u00b0 Mason.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128002739/http://bishop.house.gov/display.cfm?content_id=3|title=Congressman Sanford Bishop, Jr.|date=2005-11-28|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Bishop announced he was diagnosed as having [[lymph node]] cancer after discovering a lump in near the base of his neck. By January 2014, Bishop said that he was cancer free.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanford Bishop Announces Cancer Diagnosis, Treatments |url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/sanford_bishop_announces_cancer_diagnosis_treatments-228362-1.html|work=Roll Call |accessdate=14 March 2014|author=Hannah Hess|date=October 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanford Bishop now cancer free |url=http://www.ledger-enquirer.com/2014/01/09/2892223/sanford-bishop-now-cancer-free.html|work=Columbus Ledger-Enquirer |accessdate=14 March 2014|author=Larry Gierer|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia legislature==\nHe was elected to the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] in 1977, where he remained until being elected to the [[Georgia Senate]] in 1990.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1992\nAfter only one term in the state senate, he ran for the 2nd District in 1992, which was held by six-term U.S. Congressman [[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]], a white moderate Democrat. The 2nd had been reconfigured as a black-majority district during [[congressional apportionment]] following the [[United States Census, 1990|1990 Census]]. Bishop finished second behind Hatcher in a crowded six-way primary. Hatcher failed to reach the 50% threshold, and was forced into a runoff election. During the campaign Bishop attacked Hatcher for bouncing 819 checks in the [[House banking scandal]]. Bishop defeated him 53%-47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207815 |title=GA District 2 - D Runoff Race - Aug 11, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Republican Jim Dudley 64%-36%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27825 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nIn the Democratic primary, he defeated James Bush 67%-33%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=542481 |title=GA District 2 - D Primary Race - Jul 19, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> In the general election, he won re-election to a second term with 66%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28770 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1996\nIn 1995, a 5-4 majority of the Supreme Court ruled that the redistricting of Georgia had violated the equal protection clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]. The 2nd district was thus redrawn. The newly redrawn district was 60% white. Nonetheless, he won re-election to a third term with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29458 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1998\nBishop won re-election to a fourth term against Republican [[Joseph F. McCormick]] with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30413 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> During the campaign, Bishop received twice the campaign financing that his opponent raised.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Campaign Finance: Joseph F McCormick|url=http://influenceexplorer.com/politician/joseph-f-mccormick-r/8b33ebd9325f44418fa86e97e3f5ba77?cycle=1998|website=Influenceexplorer.com|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cycle Fundraising, 1997 - 1998, Campaign Cmte|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00002674&cycle=1998|publisher=OpenSecrets.org|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2000\nBishop defeated [[Dylan Glenn]], a young black Republican who received strong backing from many national Republican leaders. The vote was 53%-47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=339 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 07, 2000 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2002\nBishop won re-election to a sixth term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=998 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2004\nBishop won re-election to a seventh term with 67% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4097 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2006#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2008#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2010#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2012#District 2}}\nHe won re-election to an eighth term with 68% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206827 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n\nBishop won re-election to a ninth term with 69% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387943 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n\nBishop won re-election to a tenth term against Republican [[Georgia House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Mike Keown]], 51%-49%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488507 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> the closest margin of his career. In a year where the Democrats lost the majority in the house, the New York Times noted that Bishop's re-election possibilities seemed slim as an \"incumbent in an anti-Washington year\", his identity as a black man in a majority white district (49% White,47% Black), and the scholarship scandal surrounding his non-profit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rare Winner for Southern Democrats|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/05/us/politics/05georgia.html?_r=1|publisher=The New York TImes|accessdate=16 April 2012|author=Robbie Brown|date=November 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n\nAfter redistricting, the 2nd district has once again become a black majority district.  Notably, it added most of Macon, previously the heart of the 8th District.  Bishop was heavily favored in the general election as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/179503-the-10-house-members-most-helped-by-redistricting |title=House members most helped by redistricting |publisher=TheHill |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>  As expected, he defeated Republican John House with 63 percent of the vote.\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Rep Sanford Bishop.jpg|thumb|Bishop during the [[103rd United States Congress|103rd Congress]]]]\nBishop is one of the more conservative black Democrats in the House.  He is a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> as well as the [[Blue Dog Democrats]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://bluedogcaucus-costa.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Blue Dog Coalition|date=|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> a group of moderate to conservative House Democrats. Due to his willingness to work across the aisle, Congressman Bishop was ranked the 16th most bipartisan member of the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]]. The ranking was part of the Bipartisan Index put forth by [[The Lugar Center]] in collaboration with Georgetown University.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> Serving a primarily agricultural district, Bishop has fought to preserve the federal price supports for [[peanut]]s, southwest Georgia's most important crop. ''The New York Times'' quoted Mr. Adams, chairman of the agency that administers Federal farm programs in Georgia saying \"It's questionable whether it would have survived without the votes he brought to it\".<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Rural White South, Seeds of a Biracial Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/30/us/in-the-rural-white-south-seeds-of-a-biracial-politics.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Kevin Sack|date=December 30, 1998}}</ref> In 1997, he caused considerable controversy within his own party by cosponsoring a bill by U.S. Representative [[Ernest Istook]] (R-[[Oklahoma]]) to introduce a constitutional amendment to protect religious expression on public property, known as the H. J. Res, 78, the Religious Freedom Amendment. The specific wording of the amendment allowing the practice of religion on public property, most notably public schools, reads as follows:\n\n<blockquote>To secure the people's fight to acknowledge God according to the dictates of conscience: The people's right to pray and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage and traditions shall not be infringed. The Government shall not require any person to join in prayer or other religious activity, prescribe school prayers, discriminate- against religion, or deny equal access to a benefit on account of religion ... The people's right to pray and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage, or traditions on public property, including schools, shall not be infringed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testimony of Representative Sanford Bishop 2nd District, Georgia|url=http://judiciary.house.gov/legacy/22326.htm|publisher=House of Representatives Committee on the Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Sanford Bishop|date=July 22, 1997|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521202030/http://judiciary.house.gov/legacy/22326.htm|archivedate=May 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nOn October 10, 2002, Sanford Bishop was one of only four of 36 Congressional Black Caucus members who voted for the [[Iraq Resolution|joint resolution]] authorizing the [[Iraq War]]. The other three Congressional Black Caucus members who voted for the resolution authorizing the Iraq War are no longer members of Congress: [[William J. Jefferson|Bill Jefferson]] of [[Louisiana]], [[Albert Wynn]] of [[Maryland]], and [[Harold Ford, Jr.]] of [[Tennessee]].<!--\n  --><ref>{{cite web|date=October 10, 2002 |title=Final vote results for roll call 455 |publisher=[[Clerk of the United States House of Representatives]] |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2002/roll455.xml}}</ref><!--\n  --><ref>{{cite web|date=October 16, 2002 |title=H.J.RES.114 To authorize the use of United States Armed Forces against Iraq |publisher=[[THOMAS]] |url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d107:HJ00114:}}</ref><!--\n  --><ref>{{Cite news|author=Eversley, Melanie |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Georgians in House divided on Iraq  |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |page=A1 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?s_hidethis=no&p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_field_label-0=Author&p_field_label-1=title&p_bool_label-1=AND&p_text_label-1=Georgians%20in%20House%20divided%20on%20Iraq&s_dispstring=headline(Georgians%20in%20House%20divided%20on%20Iraq)%20AND%20date(all)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no |quote=Democrat Sanford Bishop unabashedly announced his support of the current Republican president.}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2007, Sanford Bishop endorsed [[Barack Obama]] for President and was co-chair of Georgia for Obama campaign; Bishop's wife, Vivian Creighton Bishop, a municipal court clerk in Columbus, was co-chair of the Georgia Women for [[Hillary Clinton|Hillary]] committee.<!--\n  --><ref>{{Cite news|author=Dewan, Shaila |date=January 18, 2008 |title=Southern Blacks Are Split on Clinton vs. Obama |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/18/us/politics/18south.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin}}</ref> However, he joined with other pro-life Democrats who voted no on President Obama's [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] because of wording in the bill that permits federal funding for Abortions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Health Care Bill Dead on Arrival, Pro-Life House Democrats Say|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/03/10/senate-health-care-dead-arrival-say-pro-life-house-democrats/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Carl Cameron|date=March 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nIn September, 2010, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Bishop had, between 2003 and 2005, directed scholarships and awards funded by the [[Congressional Black Caucus]] to ineligible persons, including his stepdaughter, Aayesha Owens Reese, his niece, Emmaundia J. Whitaker, and other people with close ties to the family, threatening to turn the program into a larger political problem for the party. Ashton McRae released a statement by Bishop's office: \"It is our understanding that the CBC Foundation in 2008 revisited the guidelines and processes for its scholarship programs, and as such, included language to clarify that CBC family members are not eligible to receive the scholarships. These scholarships ... were awarded prior to 2008.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Scher |first=Bill |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0910/41953.html |title=Bishop steered scholarships to family |website=Politico.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> Ultimately Rep. Bishop's spokesman said the congressman would repay the scholarship fund for any awards he made in violation of the rules.<ref>\"Representative Sanford D Bishop Jr Awarded Scholarships to Family\", by the Associated Press, ''New York Times'' 11 September 2010</ref> [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] mentioned Bishop in its annual Most Corrupt Members of Congress report in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Sanford Bishop (D-GA) Earned Dishonorable Mention in CREW's Annual Most Corrupt Report|url=http://www.citizensforethics.org/press/entry/sanford-bishop-earns-dishonorable-mention-most-corrupt|publisher=Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington|accessdate=16 May 2012|agency=Associated Press|date=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120803121314/http://www.citizensforethics.org/press/entry/sanford-bishop-earns-dishonorable-mention-most-corrupt|archivedate=August 3, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the [[Pigford v. Glickman]] lawsuit came out of legislative discrimination of black farmers, the case was led by Timothy Pigford and 400 black farmers. ''[[The Washington Times]]'' reported that by the end of the case in 1999, over 94,000 claims were filed in conjuncture with the original case, \"even though the [[U.S. Census Bureau]] never counted more than 33,000 black farmers in America during the years in question.\"<ref name=\"The Washington Times\">{{cite web|title=EDITORIAL: USDA's Pigford fraud Obama initiative ignores corruption to redistribute wealth|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/feb/2/usda-s-pigford-fraud/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=22 May 2012|date=February 2, 2011}}</ref> In 2007, then Senator Barack Obama passed legislation to increase the amount of money given via Pigford II. Since then reports from multiple news sources have reported on the growing reports of fraud within the program. In February 2011, three farmers brought these allegations of fraud to Mr. Bishop, including Eddie Slaughter, vice president of the Black Farmers and Agriculturalists Association, Bishop responded with \"yes, I am aware that there is fraud in the program, that's why anti-fraud provisions were written into the settlement ... It's not my job to monitor fraud in the program.\"<ref name=\"The Washington Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Blue Dog Congressman Sanford Bishop Knew About Pigford Fraud|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/lee-stranahan/blue-dog-congressman-sanf_b_812884.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=22 May 2012|author=Lee Stranahan|date=January 24, 2011}}</ref> Interviews with Mr. Slaughter have circulated the internet and criticism has been raised regarding his comments about fraud allegations leading the end of the program.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Bishop takes heat over Breitbart videos about black farmers settlement|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/georgia-politics-elections/rep-bishop-takes-heat-810415.html|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=22 May 2012|author=Bob Keefe|date=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, and Related Agencies]]\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Congressional Black Caucus]]\n*Congressional Diabetes Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*Congressional Cement Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n*[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus|date=|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n*2015 - Bishop was appointed as a Member of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem]] by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]]<ref name=\"LG 24 July 2015\">{{London Gazette |issue=61305 |date=24 July 2015 |pages=13771\u201313773}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sanford Bishop}}\n*[http://bishop.house.gov/ Congressman Sanford Bishop Jr.] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.sanfordbishop.com Sanford Bishop for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Sanford_Bishop_%5BD-2%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=b000490 |votesmart=26817 |fec=H2GA02031 |congress=sanford-bishop/91}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Georgia|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Georgia's 2nd congressional district]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Cooper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=23rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ken Calvert]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{GA Federal Representatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Sanford}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Emory University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) state senators]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Georgia House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Albany, Georgia]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Serving Brothers of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Sanford Bishop\n|image         = Sanford Bishop.jpg\n|state         = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|district      = {{ushr|GA|2|2nd}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 1993\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = Georgia\n|district1     = 15th\n|term_start1   = January 3, 1991\n|term_end1     = January 3, 1993\n|predecessor1  = Gary Parker \n|successor1    = [[Ed Harbison]]\n|state_house2  = Georgia\n|district2     = 94th\n|term_start2   = January 3, 1977\n|term_end2     = January 3, 1991\n|predecessor2  = C. Ed Berry\n|successor2    = Bill Lee\n|birth_name    = Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1947|2|4}}\n|birth_place   = [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = Vivian Creighton\n|children      = 1\n|education     = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Emory University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 1968\u20131971\n}}\n'''Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.''' (born February 4, 1947) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|GA|2}}, serving since 1993. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. The district is located in the southwestern part of the state and includes [[Albany, Georgia|Albany]], [[Thomasville, Georgia|Thomasville]], and most of [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]] and [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nBishop was born in [[Mobile, Alabama]] to Minnie B. Slade and Sanford Dixon Bishop,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~battle/reps/bishopsd.htm |title=1. Sanford Dixon Bishop Jr.: b. 4 Feb 1947 Mobile, Mobile Co., AL; U.S. Representative from GA (D)|website=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> who was the first president of [[Bishop State Community College]]. He was educated at [[Morehouse College]] and [[Emory University School of Law]], and served in the [[United States Army]].<ref name=\"navyleague\">{{cite web| title = Veterans in the US House of Representatives 109th Congress|publisher=Navy League|url=http://www.navyleague.org/legislative_affairs/HouseVets.pdf|format=PDF |accessdate=2007-10-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626235918/http://www.navyleague.org/legislative_affairs/HouseVets.pdf|archivedate=2007-06-26}}</ref> While at Morehouse, he was a classmate of [[Herman Cain]]. After receiving his honorable discharge, Bishop operated a law firm in [[Columbus, Georgia]].\n\nHe has received the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] from the [[Boy Scouts of America]] (BSA), given to [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scouts]] for distinguished career achievement.<ref name=\"honor\">{{Cite book|last=Townley|first=Alvin |url=http://www.thomasdunnebooks.com/TD_TitleDetail.aspx?ISBN=0312366531|title=Legacy of Honor: The Values and Influence of America's Eagle Scouts|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|pages=165\u201372|isbn=0-312-36653-1|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\"desalista\">{{cite web |url = http://www.scouting.org/filestore/pdf/02-529.pdf |title = Distinguished Eagle Scouts |publisher=Scouting.org|accessdate = 2010-11-04}}</ref> He is a member of BSA's [[Order of the Arrow]] (OA) and as a youth was on the OA ceremonies team.<ref name=\"honor\"/> He is a resident of [[Albany, Georgia]], where he is a member of the Mount Zion Baptist Church.  Bishop is a Life Member of [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity, initiated at Morehouse's Pi chapter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070530220133/http://bishop.house.gov/Bishop-photogallery.cfm?CD=21&ImgID=34&StartRow=4|title=Congressman Sanford Bishop, Jr.|date=2007-05-30|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>  Bishop is a [[Shriner]] and 33\u00b0 Mason.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128002739/http://bishop.house.gov/display.cfm?content_id=3|title=Congressman Sanford Bishop, Jr.|date=2005-11-28|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Bishop announced he was diagnosed as having [[lymph node]] cancer after discovering a lump in near the base of his neck. By January 2014, Bishop said that he was cancer free.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanford Bishop Announces Cancer Diagnosis, Treatments |url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/sanford_bishop_announces_cancer_diagnosis_treatments-228362-1.html|work=Roll Call |accessdate=14 March 2014|author=Hannah Hess|date=October 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanford Bishop now cancer free |url=http://www.ledger-enquirer.com/2014/01/09/2892223/sanford-bishop-now-cancer-free.html|work=Columbus Ledger-Enquirer |accessdate=14 March 2014|author=Larry Gierer|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia legislature==\nHe was elected to the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] in 1977, where he remained until being elected to the [[Georgia Senate]] in 1990.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1992\nAfter only one term in the state senate, he ran for the 2nd District in 1992, which was held by six-term U.S. Congressman [[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]], a white moderate Democrat. The 2nd had been reconfigured as a black-majority district during [[congressional apportionment]] following the [[United States Census, 1990|1990 Census]]. Bishop finished second behind Hatcher in a crowded six-way primary. Hatcher failed to reach the 50% threshold, and was forced into a runoff election. During the campaign Bishop attacked Hatcher for bouncing 819 checks in the [[House banking scandal]]. Bishop defeated him 53%-47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207815 |title=GA District 2 - D Runoff Race - Aug 11, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Republican Jim Dudley 64%-36%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27825 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nIn the Democratic primary, he defeated James Bush 67%-33%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=542481 |title=GA District 2 - D Primary Race - Jul 19, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> In the general election, he won re-election to a second term with 66%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28770 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1996\nIn 1995, a 5-4 majority of the Supreme Court ruled that the redistricting of Georgia had violated the equal protection clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]. The 2nd district was thus redrawn. The newly redrawn district was 60% white. Nonetheless, he won re-election to a third term with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29458 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;1998\nBishop won re-election to a fourth term against Republican [[Joseph F. McCormick]] with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30413 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> During the campaign, Bishop received twice the campaign financing that his opponent raised.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Campaign Finance: Joseph F McCormick|url=http://influenceexplorer.com/politician/joseph-f-mccormick-r/8b33ebd9325f44418fa86e97e3f5ba77?cycle=1998|website=Influenceexplorer.com|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cycle Fundraising, 1997 - 1998, Campaign Cmte|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00002674&cycle=1998|publisher=OpenSecrets.org|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2000\nBishop defeated [[Dylan Glenn]], a young black Republican who received strong backing from many national Republican leaders. The vote was 53%-47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=339 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 07, 2000 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2002\nBishop won re-election to a sixth term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=998 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2004\nBishop won re-election to a seventh term with 67% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4097 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2006#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2008#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2010#District 2|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2012#District 2}}\nHe won re-election to an eighth term with 68% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206827 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n\nBishop won re-election to a ninth term with 69% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387943 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n\nBishop won re-election to a tenth term against Republican [[Georgia House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Mike Keown]], 51%-49%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488507 |title=GA District 2 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> the closest margin of his career. In a year where the Democrats lost the majority in the house, the New York Times noted that Bishop's re-election possibilities seemed slim as an \"incumbent in an anti-Washington year\", his identity as a black man in a majority white district (49% White,47% Black), and the scholarship scandal surrounding his non-profit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rare Winner for Southern Democrats|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/05/us/politics/05georgia.html?_r=1|publisher=The New York TImes|accessdate=16 April 2012|author=Robbie Brown|date=November 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n\nAfter redistricting, the 2nd district has once again become a black majority district.  Notably, it added most of Macon, previously the heart of the 8th District.  Bishop was heavily favored in the general election as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/179503-the-10-house-members-most-helped-by-redistricting |title=House members most helped by redistricting |publisher=TheHill |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref>  As expected, he defeated Republican John House with 63 percent of the vote.\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Rep Sanford Bishop.jpg|thumb|Bishop during the [[103rd United States Congress|103rd Congress]]]]\nBishop is one of the more conservative black Democrats in the House.  He is a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> as well as the [[Blue Dog Democrats]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://bluedogcaucus-costa.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Blue Dog Coalition|date=|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> a group of moderate to conservative House Democrats. Due to his willingness to work across the aisle, Congressman Bishop was ranked the 16th most bipartisan member of the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]]. The ranking was part of the Bipartisan Index put forth by [[The Lugar Center]] in collaboration with Georgetown University.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> Serving a primarily agricultural district, Bishop has fought to preserve the federal price supports for [[peanut]]s, southwest Georgia's most important crop. ''The New York Times'' quoted Mr. Adams, chairman of the agency that administers Federal farm programs in Georgia saying \"It's questionable whether it would have survived without the votes he brought to it\".<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Rural White South, Seeds of a Biracial Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/30/us/in-the-rural-white-south-seeds-of-a-biracial-politics.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Kevin Sack|date=December 30, 1998}}</ref> In 1997, he caused considerable controversy within his own party by cosponsoring a bill by U.S. Representative [[Ernest Istook]] (R-[[Oklahoma]]) to introduce a constitutional amendment to protect religious expression on public property, known as the H. J. Res, 78, the Religious Freedom Amendment. The specific wording of the amendment allowing the practice of religion on public property, most notably public schools, reads as follows:\n\n<blockquote>To secure the people's fight to acknowledge God according to the dictates of conscience: The people's right to pray and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage and traditions shall not be infringed. The Government shall not require any person to join in prayer or other religious activity, prescribe school prayers, discriminate- against religion, or deny equal access to a benefit on account of religion ... The people's right to pray and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage, or traditions on public property, including schools, shall not be infringed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testimony of Representative Sanford Bishop 2nd District, Georgia|url=http://judiciary.house.gov/legacy/22326.htm|publisher=House of Representatives Committee on the Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Sanford Bishop|date=July 22, 1997|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521202030/http://judiciary.house.gov/legacy/22326.htm|archivedate=May 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nOn October 10, 2002, Sanford Bishop was one of only four of 36 Congressional Black Caucus members who voted for the [[Iraq Resolution|joint resolution]] authorizing the [[Iraq War]]. The other three Congressional Black Caucus members who voted for the resolution authorizing the Iraq War are no longer members of Congress: [[William J. Jefferson|Bill Jefferson]] of [[Louisiana]], [[Albert Wynn]] of [[Maryland]], and [[Harold Ford, Jr.]] of [[Tennessee]].<!--\n  --><ref>{{cite web|date=October 10, 2002 |title=Final vote results for roll call 455 |publisher=[[Clerk of the United States House of Representatives]] |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2002/roll455.xml}}</ref><!--\n  --><ref>{{cite web|date=October 16, 2002 |title=H.J.RES.114 To authorize the use of United States Armed Forces against Iraq |publisher=[[THOMAS]] |url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d107:HJ00114:}}</ref><!--\n  --><ref>{{Cite news|author=Eversley, Melanie |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Georgians in House divided on Iraq  |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |page=A1 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?s_hidethis=no&p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_field_label-0=Author&p_field_label-1=title&p_bool_label-1=AND&p_text_label-1=Georgians%20in%20House%20divided%20on%20Iraq&s_dispstring=headline(Georgians%20in%20House%20divided%20on%20Iraq)%20AND%20date(all)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no |quote=Democrat Sanford Bishop unabashedly announced his support of the current Republican president.}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2007, Sanford Bishop endorsed [[Barack Obama]] for President and was co-chair of Georgia for Obama campaign; Bishop's wife, Vivian Creighton Bishop, a municipal court clerk in Columbus, was co-chair of the Georgia Women for [[Hillary Clinton|Hillary]] committee.<!--\n  --><ref>{{Cite news|author=Dewan, Shaila |date=January 18, 2008 |title=Southern Blacks Are Split on Clinton vs. Obama |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/18/us/politics/18south.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin}}</ref> However, he joined with other pro-life Democrats who voted no on President Obama's [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] because of wording in the bill that permits federal funding for Abortions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Health Care Bill Dead on Arrival, Pro-Life House Democrats Say|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/03/10/senate-health-care-dead-arrival-say-pro-life-house-democrats/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=2 May 2012|author=Carl Cameron|date=March 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nIn September, 2010, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Bishop had, between 2003 and 2005, directed scholarships and awards funded by the [[Congressional Black Caucus]] to ineligible persons, including his stepdaughter, Aayesha Owens Reese, his niece, Emmaundia J. Whitaker, and other people with close ties to the family, threatening to turn the program into a larger political problem for the party. Ashton McRae released a statement by Bishop's office: \"It is our understanding that the CBC Foundation in 2008 revisited the guidelines and processes for its scholarship programs, and as such, included language to clarify that CBC family members are not eligible to receive the scholarships. These scholarships ... were awarded prior to 2008.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Scher |first=Bill |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0910/41953.html |title=Bishop steered scholarships to family |website=Politico.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-31}}</ref> Ultimately Rep. Bishop's spokesman said the congressman would repay the scholarship fund for any awards he made in violation of the rules.<ref>\"Representative Sanford D Bishop Jr Awarded Scholarships to Family\", by the Associated Press, ''New York Times'' 11 September 2010</ref> [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] mentioned Bishop in its annual Most Corrupt Members of Congress report in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Sanford Bishop (D-GA) Earned Dishonorable Mention in CREW's Annual Most Corrupt Report|url=http://www.citizensforethics.org/press/entry/sanford-bishop-earns-dishonorable-mention-most-corrupt|publisher=Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington|accessdate=16 May 2012|agency=Associated Press|date=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120803121314/http://www.citizensforethics.org/press/entry/sanford-bishop-earns-dishonorable-mention-most-corrupt|archivedate=August 3, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the [[Pigford v. Glickman]] lawsuit came out of legislative discrimination of black farmers, the case was led by Timothy Pigford and 400 black farmers. ''[[The Washington Times]]'' reported that by the end of the case in 1999, over 94,000 claims were filed in conjuncture with the original case, \"even though the [[U.S. Census Bureau]] never counted more than 33,000 black farmers in America during the years in question.\"<ref name=\"The Washington Times\">{{cite web|title=EDITORIAL: USDA's Pigford fraud Obama initiative ignores corruption to redistribute wealth|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/feb/2/usda-s-pigford-fraud/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=22 May 2012|date=February 2, 2011}}</ref> In 2007, then Senator Barack Obama passed legislation to increase the amount of money given via Pigford II. Since then reports from multiple news sources have reported on the growing reports of fraud within the program. In February 2011, three farmers brought these allegations of fraud to Mr. Bishop, including Eddie Slaughter, vice president of the Black Farmers and Agriculturalists Association, Bishop responded with \"yes, I am aware that there is fraud in the program, that's why anti-fraud provisions were written into the settlement ... It's not my job to monitor fraud in the program.\"<ref name=\"The Washington Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Blue Dog Congressman Sanford Bishop Knew About Pigford Fraud|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/lee-stranahan/blue-dog-congressman-sanf_b_812884.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=22 May 2012|author=Lee Stranahan|date=January 24, 2011}}</ref> Interviews with Mr. Slaughter have circulated the internet and criticism has been raised regarding his comments about fraud allegations leading the end of the program.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Bishop takes heat over Breitbart videos about black farmers settlement|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/georgia-politics-elections/rep-bishop-takes-heat-810415.html|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=22 May 2012|author=Bob Keefe|date=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Rural Development, Food and Drug Administration, and Related Agencies]]\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Congressional Black Caucus]]\n*Congressional Diabetes Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*Congressional Cement Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n*[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus|date=|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n*2015 - Bishop was appointed as a Member of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem]] by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]]<ref name=\"LG 24 July 2015\">{{London Gazette |issue=61305 |date=24 July 2015 |pages=13771\u201313773}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sanford Bishop}}\n*[http://bishop.house.gov/ Congressman Sanford Bishop Jr.] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.sanfordbishop.com Sanford Bishop for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Sanford_Bishop_%5BD-2%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=b000490 |votesmart=26817 |fec=H2GA02031 |congress=sanford-bishop/91}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Floyd Hatcher|Charles Hatcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Georgia|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Georgia's 2nd congressional district]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Cooper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=23rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ken Calvert]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{GA Federal Representatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Sanford}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Emory University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) state senators]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Georgia House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Albany, Georgia]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Serving Brothers of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "Tanstaboi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanford_Bishop"}
{"title_page": "Evan Niland", "text_new": "{{infobox GAA player\n|image           =\n|name            = Evan Niland\n|irish           = \u00c9imh\u00edn \u00d3 Niall\u00e1in\n|nickname        = \n|occupation      = Student\n|birth_date      = 1998\n|birth_place     = [[Clarinbridge]], [[County Galway]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|height          = \n|sport           = Hurling\n|code            = Hurling\n|county          = Galway\n|province        = Leinster\n|club            = [[Clarinbridge GAA|Clarinbridge]]\n|clyears         = 2015-present\n|clposition      = \n|clapps(points)  = 31 (2-287)\n|clcounty        = 0\n|clprovince      = \n|clallireland    =\n|colleges        = [[NUI Galway GAA|NUI Galway]]\n|fitz            = 0\n|colyears        = 2017-present\n|counties        = [[Galway GAA|Galway]]\n|icyears         = 2019-present\n|icposition      = Full-forward\n|icapps(points)  = 0 (0-00)\t\n|icprovince      = 0\n|icallireland    = 0\n|nhl             = 0\n|allstars        = 0 \n|clupdate        = \n|icupdate        = 16:01, 13 January 2020\n}}\n'''Evan Niland''' (born 1998) is an Irish [[hurling|hurler]] who plays for [[Galway Senior Hurling Championship|Galway Senior Championship]] club [[Clarinbridge GAA|Clarinbridge]] and at inter-county level with the [[Galway senior hurling team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connachttribune.ie/63108-2-444/|title=Niland\u2019s free bails Clarinbridge boys out of trouble|publisher=Connacht Tribune|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=13 January 2020|first=Alan|last=Dooley}}</ref> He usually lines out as a full-forward. Evan recently took up an ambassadorial role in Small Jobs ltd. He is rocking a buzz cut these days although the woman isn\u2019t overly impressed with it.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n\n{{updated|match played 29 September 2019.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Galway Senior Hurling Championship|Galway SHC]]\n|-\